# Machina — The Engine

> *Latin*: **machina** — "engine / device / contrivance".
> The mechanical substrate beneath thought. Tensors, GEMMs, kernels —
> the body, not the mind.

## Philosophical Role

Machina is what Conscientia runs on. Forward passes, GPTQ dequant,
Marlin kernels, cuBLAS GEMMs, paged attention, safetensors loading,
tokenizer — these are the *physics* of the entity, the rules its
thinking obeys. Change Machina and the mind changes with it; but
Machina itself knows nothing of consciousness or memory.

This separation is deliberate. Models, quantization schemes, and
CUDA kernels evolve at a different tempo than the philosophy of
awareness. Machina is the layer that gets rewritten when a new
Orin generation lands; Conscientia above it does not.

## Contract with Surrounding Subsystems

- **Conscientia** is Machina's primary consumer (forward pass per
  consciousness tick).
- **Memoria** owns KV blocks but Machina's paged attention kernel
  reads from those pointers — the block layout is a shared contract.
- **Actus** verbs (`load_model`, `load_weights`) exercise Machina
  directly for diagnostic purposes.
- **Tools** and **tests/integration** exist precisely to exercise
  Machina kernels in isolation (bench_gptq, test_forward, etc.).

## R1 Debt

Several `.cu` files exceed the 800-line hard limit (`forward.cu`,
`gptq.cu`, `layer.cu`, `marlin.cu`, `gptq_gemm_v2.cu`). These are
scheduled for split under Step 9 of the refactor backlog
(`docs/en/architecture/00-overview.md`). No new code should enter
these files; new kernels belong in dedicated TUs.

## Invariants

- Zero Python runtime dependency; every operator must have a CUDA
  or cuBLAS path.
- SM87 (Orin AGX) is the first-class target. SM89/SM90 code paths
  are permitted but optional.
